Ah, I see what you mean now — you don’t want to work inside the .pbix file, you want to convert/export your Power BI project into another format (like Excel, PDF, or maybe a Word document) rather than keeping it as .pbix. Let’s break down the options you have:

📤 Ways to Export/Convert a Power BI File
Export to Excel

In Power BI Desktop, you can’t directly convert .pbix to .xlsx.

But if your report is published to the Power BI Service:

Go to the report → Export → Export data.

This gives you the underlying dataset in .xlsx or .csv.

Export to PDF or PowerPoint

In Power BI Desktop: File → Export → Export to PDF.

In Power BI Service: Export → PowerPoint (PPTX) or PDF.

This keeps the visuals exactly as they appear on your dashboard.

Publish to Power BI Service and Use “Analyze in Excel”

Upload your .pbix to Power BI Service.

Use the Analyze in Excel feature to connect Excel directly to your dataset.

This lets you build pivot tables and charts in Excel using your Power BI model.

Export Data Tables

Right-click on a visual → Export data.

Saves the data behind that chart as .csv.

Third-Party Tools / Scripts

Some tools or scripts can extract metadata (tables, measures, relationships) from .pbix into JSON or Excel documentation format.

Useful if you want a “data dictionary” style output.

⚡ Recommendation
If your goal is sharing dashboards → Export to PDF/PPTX.

If your goal is working with raw data in Excel → Use Export Data or Analyze in Excel.

If your goal is documenting the project → Use third-party tools to extract schema and measures.

